  "response": "Getting into MIT is highly competitive. Here are some key factors MIT considers:\n\n1. Academic Profile\n- Near-perfect GPA (typically 4.0 or close)\n- Extremely strong standardized test scores\n- Rigorous high school curriculum\n- Advanced math and science courses\n\n2. MIT's International Admission Stats\n- Acceptance rate: Around 4-7%\n- International students: Approximately 10% of admitted students\n- Highly selective for international applicants\n\n3. Key Strengths Needed\n- Outstanding academic achievements\n- Exceptional math and science skills\n- Demonstrated research or innovation\n- Strong extracurricular activities\n- Leadership experience\n- Unique personal achievements\n\n4. Competitive Academic Requirements\n- SAT/ACT scores near perfect\n- SAT Math: Typically 770-800\n- SAT Evidence-Based Reading: 730-780\n- Strong AP/IB scores\n\n5. Additional Important Factors\n- Compelling personal essays\n- Letters of recommendation\n- Demonstrated passion for STEM\n- Innovative projects or research\n\nRecommendation: Build a strong academic and extracurricular profile, showcase unique talents, and prepare a compelling application.\n\nWould you like more specific advice about your individual profile?",
